********************Annotations********************	

@component: Define a component. The component is a reusable piece of code that can be used in different parts of the application.
@configuration: Define a configuration class. A configuration class is a class that contains bean definitions and other configuration settings for the application.
@SpringBootApplication: Define a Spring Boot application. This annotation is a combination of @Configuration, @EnableAutoConfiguration, and @ComponentScan, 
	which means that it can be used to create a Spring Boot application with minimal configuration.
@EnableAutoConfiguration: Enable auto-configuration. This annotation tells Spring Boot to automatically configure the application based on the dependencies that are present in the classpath.
@ComponentScan: Enable component scanning. This annotation tells Spring to scan for components, configurations, and services in the specified package and register them as beans in the application context.
@Controller: Define a controller. A controller is a class that handles incoming HTTP requests and returns responses to the client.
@RestController: Define a REST controller. A REST controller is a special type of controller that is used to create RESTful web services.
	it is a combination of @Controller and @ResponseBody, which means that it can handle HTTP requests and return JSON or XML responses.
@service: Define a service. A service is a class that provides a specific functionality and can be injected into other components or services.
@Repository: Define a repository. A repository is a class that provides an abstraction over the data access layer, allowing you to interact with the database without having to write SQL queries.

If we annotate a class service with @component instead of @service, it will still work because @service is a specialization of @component. 
However, using @service is more semantically correct and makes it clear that the class is a service component. 
It also allows for better organization and readability of the code, as it indicates the specific role of the class within the application.

If we annotate a class repository with @component instead of @repository, it will still work because @repository is a specialization of @component.
However, using @repository is more semantically correct and makes it clear that the class is a repository component.
But using @repository also provides additional benefits, such as exception translation, which means that any exceptions 
thrown by the underlying data access technology will be translated into Spring's DataAccessException hierarchy.

@controller and @restcontroller are both used to define controllers in a Spring application, but they serve different purposes.
@Controller is used to define a standard controller that handles HTTP requests and returns views (e.g., HTML pages).
@RestController is a specialized version of @Controller that is used to create RESTful web services. 
It combines the functionality of @Controller and @ResponseBody,and tells Spring to serialize the return value of the controller methods directly into the HTTP response body, typically in JSON or XML format.

@configuration and @component are both used to define beans in a Spring application, but they serve different purposes.
@Configuration is used to define a configuration class that contains bean definitions and other configuration settings for the application.
@Component is a more general annotation that can be used to define any Spring-managed component, including services, repositories, and controllers.

@profile: Define a profile. A profile is a way to group beans and configuration settings based on the environment or other criteria. 
    For example, you can define a "dev" profile for development and a "prod" profile for production, and then use the @profile annotation to specify which beans should be active in each profile.
    
@autowired: Define a dependency injection point. This annotation tells Spring to inject a bean into the annotated field, constructor, or method. 
    Spring will automatically find the appropriate bean based on the type and inject it into the class.
    
@qualifier: Define a qualifier for a bean. This annotation is used in conjunction with @autowired to specify which bean should be injected when there are multiple beans of the same type. 
    You can use the @qualifier annotation to give each bean a unique name, and then use that name to specify which bean should be injected.
    
@Primary: Define a primary bean. This annotation is used to indicate that a bean should be given preference when multiple beans of the same type are present. 
    When Spring encounters multiple beans of the same type, it will choose the one marked with @primary as the default bean to inject.

@Secondary: Define a secondary bean. This annotation is used to indicate that a bean should be given lower priority when multiple beans of the same type are present. 
    When Spring encounters multiple beans of the same type, it will choose the one marked with @primary as the default bean to inject, and the one marked with @secondary will be used as a fallback if the primary bean is not available.  
@value: Define a value to be injected into a field or method parameter. This annotation is used to inject values from properties files, environment variables, or other sources into the application.

@RequestMapping: Define a mapping for an HTTP request. This annotation is used to specify the URL path and HTTP method that a controller method should handle.
@pathvariable: Define a path variable in a URL. This annotation is used to extract a variable from the URL and pass it as a parameter to a controller method.
@requestparam: Define a request parameter. This annotation is used to extract a parameter from the query string of an HTTP request and pass it as a parameter to a controller method.
@requestbody: Define a request body. This annotation is used to extract the body of an HTTP request and pass it as a parameter to a controller method.
@responsebody: Define a response body. This annotation is used to indicate that the return value of a controller method should be serialized directly into the HTTP response body, typically in JSON or XML format.

@exceptionhandler: Define an exception handler. This annotation is used to specify a method that should handle exceptions thrown by controller methods.
@RestControllerAdvice: Define a controller advice. This annotation is used to specify a class that contains global exception handling and other cross-cutting concerns for controllers.

@Entity: Define an entity. This annotation is used to specify that a class is an entity that should be mapped to a database table.
@table: Define a table. This annotation is used to specify the name of the database table that an entity should be mapped to.
@id: Define a primary key. This annotation is used to specify the primary key field of an entity.`
@GeneratedValue: Define a generated value. This annotation is used to specify that the value of a primary key should be generated automatically by the database.
@column: Define a column. This annotation is used to specify the name of the database column that a field should be mapped to.
@transient: Define a transient field. This annotation is used to indicate that a field should not be persisted to the database.
@lombok: Define a Lombok annotation. Lombok is a library that provides annotations to reduce boilerplate code in Java classes, such as getters, setters, constructors, and more.
@data: Define a Lombok @Data annotation. This annotation generates getters, setters, toString, equals, and hashCode methods for a class.
@builder: Define a Lombok @Builder annotation. This annotation generates a builder pattern for a class, allowing you to create instances of the class using a fluent API.
@allargsconstructor: Define a Lombok @AllArgsConstructor annotation. This annotation generates a constructor with parameters for all fields in the class.
@noargsconstructor: Define a Lombok @NoArgsConstructor annotation. This annotation generates a constructor with no parameters for the class.

@oneof: Define a conditional bean. This annotation is used to specify that a bean should only be created if certain conditions are met, such as the presence of another bean or a specific property value.
@conditional: Define a conditional bean. This annotation is used to specify that a bean should only be created if certain conditions are met, such as the presence of another bean or a specific property value.
@onlyifbean: Define a conditional bean. This annotation is used to specify that a bean should only be created if a specific bean is present in the application context.
@onlyifproperty: Define a conditional bean. This annotation is used to specify that a bean should only be created if a specific property has a certain value.
@onlyifexpression: Define a conditional bean. This annotation is used to specify that a bean should only be created if a specific SpEL expression evaluates to true.

@onetoone: Define a one-to-one relationship between two entities. This annotation is used to specify that each instance of one entity is associated with exactly one instance of another entity.
@onetomany: Define a one-to-many relationship between two entities. This annotation is used to specify that each instance of one entity is associated with multiple instances of another entity.
@manytoone: Define a many-to-one relationship between two entities. This annotation is used to specify that multiple instances of one entity are associated with a single instance of another entity.
@manytomany: Define a many-to-many relationship between two entities. This annotation is used to specify that multiple instances of one entity are associated with multiple instances of another entity.
@joincolumn: Define a join column. This annotation is used to specify the column that should be used to join two entities in a relationship.
@joinTable: Define a join table. This annotation is used to specify the table that should be used to join two entities in a many-to-many relationship.
@mappedBy: Define the owning side of a relationship. This annotation is used to specify which entity is the owner of a relationship in a bidirectional association.
@JsonIgnore: Define a JSON ignore property. This annotation is used to indicate that a field should be ignored when serializing an object to JSON, preventing it from being included in the JSON output.
@JsonManagedReference: Define a JSON managed reference. This annotation is used to indicate that a field is the parent side of a bidirectional relationship, allowing it to be serialized without causing infinite recursion.
@JsonBackReference: Define a JSON back reference. This annotation is used to indicate that a field is the child side of a bidirectional relationship, preventing it from being serialized and causing infinite recursion.
